The curators of China and Saudi Arabia jointly held the first Saudi Contemporary Art Biennal-Xinhuanet Xinhua Agency, Riyadh, December 12 thThe first Saudi Arabia contemporary art biennale, the Diriyah Contemporary Art Biennale, opened to the public on Monday at the JAX Art Zone in Diriyah, northwest of Riyadh, the capital of Saudi Arabia. A total of 64 artists from Saudi Arabia and China participated in the exhibition. The Biennale is jointly organized by the Saudi Arabia Diriyah Biennale Foundation and the UCCA Center for Contemporary Art in China.Tian Feiyu, curator of UCCA Center for Contemporary Art in China, is the artistic director. According to the curatorial team, the theme of the Biennale is "Crossing the River by Feeling the Stones", which symbolizes the reform strategy adopted during the period of social and economic transformation and reflects the current situation of social and cultural development in Saudi Arabia."Crossing the River by Feeling the Stones","Inheritance as Experiment","Marginal Thinking","Going to the Public","Brave New World" and "On the Spirit of Art". Among them, the works of 27 Saudi artists account for more than 40% of the total exhibits, including painting, installation art and performing art;The works of 12 China artists have also attracted much attention, some of whom use recycled materials in novel ways, such as Xu Bing 's "The Story Behind the Series"(2014), a classic landscape painting was reconstructed from waste. Barkley, CEO of the Diriyah Biennale Foundation, expressed the hope that this year 's Biennale will establish an international dialogue and give global audiences the opportunity to learn about Saudi Arabia' s thriving cultural industry and creative community and strengthen interaction. Tian Feiyu said:"The Biennale aims to engage Saudi contemporary art in a global dialogue and to integrate Saudi audiences into the contemporary art world." It is understood that a series of lectures will be held during the opening week of the Biennale, where artists, curators and opinion leaders from the creative industry will discuss topics such as cross-cultural exchange and contemporary art development.
